{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f84c235f-555f-4396-9c81-20c133fe2b0b","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test, Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test, Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic Task MyTunitTest() => Task.CompletedTask;\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit uses a **property** on the test attribute rather than a separate attribute. TUnit uses `Skip` instead of `Ignore`. MSTest and NUnit both use `Ignore`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ffaeaa35-8530-411a-9aed-f2b76e47d9b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test skip/ignore attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"0429:1256A4:1848218:1B92607:69E81E62"},"id":"f83e0aa1-81be-4277-b08a-3e19df7351cb","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:37.676Z","parentId":"d4cbcabf-49ca-49ae-83f4-59d23f1e7ba1"}
